              "abstract": "Machine learning in the form of inference of state machine models has gained popularity in model-based testing as a means of retrieving models from software systems. By combining an old idea from machine inference with methods from automata testing in a heuristic approach, we propose a new promising direction for inferring black box systems that cannot be reset. Preliminary experiments show that this heuristic approach scales up well and outperforms more systematic approaches.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 13th International Workshop on Automation of Software Test AST 2018 Revisiting AI and Testing Methods to Infer FSM Models of Black-Box Systems 1521276864750 Roland Groz Université Grenoble Alpes Roland.Groz@univ-grenoble-alpes.fr Adenilso Simao Universidade de Sao Paulo Adenilso@icmc.usp.br Nicolas Bremond Université Grenoble Alpes Nicolas.Bremond2@univ-grenoble-alpes.fr Catherine Oriat Université Grenoble Alpes Catherine.Oriat@imag.fr Query learning FSM Testing Software Engineering Machine learning in the form of inference of state machine models has gained popularity in model-based testing as a means of retrieving models from software systems. By combining an old idea from machine inference with methods from automata testing in a heuristic approach, we propose a new promising direction for inferring black box systems that cannot be reset. Preliminary experiments show that this heuristic approach scales up well and outperforms more systematic approaches.",
