            {
              "id": "6WCvg27RBOcUk7Et2Wc1UG",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "Neutrality and Epistasis in Program Space",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/GI2018-3UOURZbXQAKk2l55GqHdzu/7urvfjXkcYPj7tqkMGUQ82/6S9W5CUxTS0JvqTga5Mg7n.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Joseph Renzullo (Arizona State University), Westley Weimer (University of Michigan), Melanie Moses (University of New Mexico), Stephanie Forrest (Arizona State University)",
              "abstract": "Neutral networks in biology often contain diverse solutions with equal fitness, which can be useful when environments (requirements) change over time. In this paper, we present a method for studying neutral networks in software. In these networks, we find multiple solutions to held-out test cases (latent bugs), suggesting that neutral software networks also exhibit relevant diversity. We also observe instances of positive epistasis between random mutations, i.e. interactions that collectively increase fitness. Positive epistasis is rare as a fraction of the total search space but significant as a fraction of the objective space: 9% of the repairs we found to look (and 4.63% across all programs analyzed) were produced by positive interactions between mutations. Further, the majority (62.50%) of unique repairs are instances of positive epistasis.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 4th International Genetic Improvement Workshop GI 2018 Neutrality and Epistasis in Program Space 1521494818385 Joseph Renzullo Arizona State University renzullo@asu.edu Westley Weimer University of Michigan weimerw@umich.edu Melanie Moses University of New Mexico melaniem@cs.unm.edu Stephanie Forrest Arizona State University stephanie.forrest@asu.edu Software evolution Biological networks Software testing and debugging network science Automated software engineering Neutral networks in biology often contain diverse solutions with equal fitness, which can be useful when environments (requirements) change over time. In this paper, we present a method for studying neutral networks in software. In these networks, we find multiple solutions to held-out test cases (latent bugs), suggesting that neutral software networks also exhibit relevant diversity. We also observe instances of positive epistasis between random mutations, i.e. interactions that collectively increase fitness. Positive epistasis is rare as a fraction of the total search space but significant as a fraction of the objective space: 9% of the repairs we found to look (and 4.63% across all programs analyzed) were produced by positive interactions between mutations. Further, the majority (62.50%) of unique repairs are instances of positive epistasis.",
              "pageNumber": 1,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            },
            {
              "id": "4ksL3Sydt9fMDijZnlLng0",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "Experiments in Genetic Divergence for Emergent Systems",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/GI2018-3UOURZbXQAKk2l55GqHdzu/3U7Uf0gqUAyFo9y5l9mGuM/3grmQLT0F02ZQ0WEO8E22x.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Christopher McGowan (Lancaster University), Alexander Wild (Lancaster University), Barry Porter (Lancaster University)",
              "abstract": "Emergent software systems take a step towards tackling the everincreasing complexity of modern software, by having systems self-assemble from a library of building blocks, and then continually re-assemble themselves from alternative building blocks to learn which compositions of behaviour work best in each deployment environment. One of the key challenges in emergent systems is populating the library of building blocks, and particularly a set of alternative implementations of particular building blocks, which form the runtime search space of optimal behaviour. We present initial work in using a fusion of genetic improvement and genetic synthesis to automatically populate a divergent set of implementations of the same functionality, allowing emergent systems to explore new behavioural alternatives without human input. Our early results indicate this approach is able to successfully yield useful divergent implementations of building blocks which are more suited than any existing alternative for particular operating conditions.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 4th International Genetic Improvement Workshop GI 2018 Experiments in Genetic Divergence for Emergent Systems 1521218512692 Christopher McGowan Lancaster University christopherdavidmcgowan@gmail.com Alexander Wild Lancaster University a.wild3@lancaster.ac.uk Barry Porter Lancaster University b.f.porter@lancaster.ac.uk emergent systems genetic improvement Emergent software systems take a step towards tackling the everincreasing complexity of modern software, by having systems self-assemble from a library of building blocks, and then continually re-assemble themselves from alternative building blocks to learn which compositions of behaviour work best in each deployment environment. One of the key challenges in emergent systems is populating the library of building blocks, and particularly a set of alternative implementations of particular building blocks, which form the runtime search space of optimal behaviour. We present initial work in using a fusion of genetic improvement and genetic synthesis to automatically populate a divergent set of implementations of the same functionality, allowing emergent systems to explore new behavioural alternatives without human input. Our early results indicate this approach is able to successfully yield useful divergent implementations of building blocks which are more suited than any existing alternative for particular operating conditions.",
              "pageNumber": 9,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            },
            {
              "id": "24UKzjeZ49JN3YCKusNGVC",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "A Turing Test for Genetic Improvement",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/GI2018-3UOURZbXQAKk2l55GqHdzu/eW3SlYZMYS6cMCwQzW0hm/1Ys3Wy5I4MKaXKwTEWZdb7.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Afsoon Afzal (Carnegie Mellon University), Jeremy Lacomis (Carnegie Mellon University), Claire Le Goues (Carnegie Mellon University), Christopher Steven Timperley (Carnegie Mellon University)",
              "abstract": "Genetic improvement is a research field that aims to develop search-based techniques for improving existing code. GI has been used to automatically repair bugs, reduce energy consumption, and to improve run-time performance. In this paper, we reflect on the often-overlooked relationship between GI and developers within the context of continually evolving software systems. We introduce a distinction between transparent and opaque patches based on intended lifespan and developer interaction. Finally, we outline a Turing test for assessing the ability of a GI system to produce opaque patches that are acceptable to humans. This motivates research into the role GI systems will play in transparent development contexts.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 4th International Genetic Improvement Workshop GI 2018 A Turing Test for Genetic Improvement 1521494663686 Afsoon Afzal Carnegie Mellon University afsoona@cs.cmu.edu Jeremy Lacomis Carnegie Mellon University jlacomis@cs.cmu.edu Claire Le Goues Carnegie Mellon University clegoues@cs.cmu.edu Christopher Steven Timperley Carnegie Mellon University ctimperley@cs.cmu.edu genetic improvement program repair Turing test opaque patch transparent patch Genetic improvement is a research field that aims to develop search-based techniques for improving existing code. GI has been used to automatically repair bugs, reduce energy consumption, and to improve run-time performance. In this paper, we reflect on the often-overlooked relationship between GI and developers within the context of continually evolving software systems. We introduce a distinction between transparent and opaque patches based on intended lifespan and developer interaction. Finally, we outline a Turing test for assessing the ability of a GI system to produce opaque patches that are acceptable to humans. This motivates research into the role GI systems will play in transparent development contexts.",
              "pageNumber": 17,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            }
