              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "Creating and Evaluating a Software Power Model for Linux Single Board Computers",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/GREENS2018-jrEVQ2swLWGfDlZi1ZhDr/2lVKwwTWrd2cNWaH9KJgbn/3RPwQprRxK5BWers9DNsoE.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Luca Ardito (Politecnico di Torino), Marco Torchiano (Politecnico di Torino)",
              "abstract": "The number of Single Board Computers (SBCs) is increasing, and so is the cumulative energy consumed by this category of device. Moreover, such devices are often always-on or running on batteries. Therefore, it is worth investigating their energy consumption to provide software developers and users with indicators for understanding how much energy the device is consuming while running a software application. In this paper, we explain a procedure for the creation of an energy consumption model of SBCs based on the usage of its components. We apply the procedure on a Raspberry PI 2 model B to test the model with a set of real applications. The results demonstrate the practical feasibility of the approach and show that estimated consumption values on our device have an average error of 2.2%, which is a good approximation without using external and expensive measuring devices",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 6th International Workshop on Green And Sustainable Software GREENS 2018 Creating and Evaluating a Software Power Model for Linux Single Board Computers 1521193995911 Luca Ardito Politecnico di Torino luca.ardito@polito.it Marco Torchiano Politecnico di Torino marco.torchiano@polito.it energy consumption software energy consumption software engineering energy consumption data computer engineering The number of Single Board Computers (SBCs) is increasing, and so is the cumulative energy consumed by this category of device. Moreover, such devices are often always-on or running on batteries. Therefore, it is worth investigating their energy consumption to provide software developers and users with indicators for understanding how much energy the device is consuming while running a software application. In this paper, we explain a procedure for the creation of an energy consumption model of SBCs based on the usage of its components. We apply the procedure on a Raspberry PI 2 model B to test the model with a set of real applications. The results demonstrate the practical feasibility of the approach and show that estimated consumption values on our device have an average error of 2.2%, which is a good approximation without using external and expensive measuring devices",
