            {
              "id": "1q0hLsRx0WdDGbiC9q9FXV",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "From Operational to Declarative Specifications Using a Genetic Algorithm",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/SBST2018-77UFPTELICBMLdRdBsqxwb/5Da5lHsGqXsKWzJX3S0vDZ/6fg5bsCSBjg5nLZ21DrQx5.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Facundo Molina (CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto), Renzo Degiovanni (University of Rio Cuarto), Germán Regis (University of Rio Cuarto), Pablo Castro (CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto), Nazareno Aguirre (CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto), Marcelo Frias (CONICET and Buenos Aires Institute of Technology)",
              "abstract": "In specification-based test generation, sometimes having a formal specification is not sufficient, since the specification may be in a different formalism from that required by the generation approach being used. In this paper, we deal with this problem specifically in the context in which, while having a formal specification in the form of an operational invariant written in a sequential pro- gramming language, one needs, for test generation, a declarative invariant in a logical formalism. We propose a genetic algorithm that given a catalog of common properties of invariants, such as acyclicity, sortedness and balance, attempts to evolve a conjunction of these that most accurately approximates an original operational specification. We present some details of the algorithm, and an experimental evaluation based on a benchmark of data structures, for which we evolve declarative logical invariants from operational ones.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 11th International Workshop on Search-Based Software Testing SBST 2018 From Operational to Declarative Specifications Using a Genetic Algorithm 1521587717844 Facundo Molina CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto fmolina@dc.exa.unrc.edu.ar Renzo Degiovanni University of Rio Cuarto rdegiovanni@dc.exa.unrc.edu.ar Germán Regis University of Rio Cuarto gregis@dc.exa.unrc.edu.ar Pablo Castro CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto pcastro@dc.exa.unrc.edu.ar Nazareno Aguirre CONICET and University of Rio Cuarto naguirre@dc.exa.unrc.edu.ar Marcelo Frias CONICET and Buenos Aires Institute of Technology mfrias@itba.edu.ar Declarative Invariants Operational Invariants Genetic Algorithms In specification-based test generation, sometimes having a formal specification is not sufficient, since the specification may be in a different formalism from that required by the generation approach being used. In this paper, we deal with this problem specifically in the context in which, while having a formal specification in the form of an operational invariant written in a sequential pro- gramming language, one needs, for test generation, a declarative invariant in a logical formalism. We propose a genetic algorithm that given a catalog of common properties of invariants, such as acyclicity, sortedness and balance, attempts to evolve a conjunction of these that most accurately approximates an original operational specification. We present some details of the algorithm, and an experimental evaluation based on a benchmark of data structures, for which we evolve declarative logical invariants from operational ones.",
              "pageNumber": 39,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            },
            {
              "id": "2kM63Tl8Vx9le91u8u3DMY",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "To Call, or Not to Call: Contrasting Direct and Indirect Branch Coverage in Test Generation",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/SBST2018-77UFPTELICBMLdRdBsqxwb/58EPU05nJ5YGMYJNkecLRE/4lkJHQx2IgLWy25ID7LSxK.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Gregory Gay (University of South Carolina)",
              "abstract": "While adequacy criteria offer an end-point for testing, they do not mandate how targets are covered. Branch Coverage may be attained through direct calls to methods, or through indirect calls between methods. Automated generation is biased towards the rapid gains offered by indirect coverage. Therefore, even with the same end-goal, humans and automation produce very different tests. Direct coverage may yield tests that are more understandable, and that detect faults missed by traditional approaches. However, the added burden for the generation framework may result in lower coverage and faults that emerge through method interactions may be missed. To compare the two approaches, we have generated test suites for both, judging efficacy against real faults. We have found that requir- ing direct coverage results in lower achieved coverage and likelihood of fault detection. However, both forms of Branch Coverage cover code and detect faults that the other does not. By isolating methods, Direct Branch Coverage is less constrained in the choice of input. However, traditional Branch Coverage is able to leverage method interactions to discover faults. Ultimately, both are situationally applicable within the context of a broader testing strategy.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 11th International Workshop on Search-Based Software Testing SBST 2018 To Call, or Not to Call: Contrasting Direct and Indirect Branch Coverage in Test Generation 1521128049288 Gregory Gay University of South Carolina greg@greggay.com Adequacy Criteria Automated Test Generation Branch Coverage While adequacy criteria offer an end-point for testing, they do not mandate how targets are covered. Branch Coverage may be attained through direct calls to methods, or through indirect calls between methods. Automated generation is biased towards the rapid gains offered by indirect coverage. Therefore, even with the same end-goal, humans and automation produce very different tests. Direct coverage may yield tests that are more understandable, and that detect faults missed by traditional approaches. However, the added burden for the generation framework may result in lower coverage and faults that emerge through method interactions may be missed. To compare the two approaches, we have generated test suites for both, judging efficacy against real faults. We have found that requir- ing direct coverage results in lower achieved coverage and likelihood of fault detection. However, both forms of Branch Coverage cover code and detect faults that the other does not. By isolating methods, Direct Branch Coverage is less constrained in the choice of input. However, traditional Branch Coverage is able to leverage method interactions to discover faults. Ultimately, both are situationally applicable within the context of a broader testing strategy.",
              "pageNumber": 43,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            },
            {
              "id": "7vrTDQLWj9xPlCVv4Gtt8S",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "Generating Test Input with Deep Reinforcement Learning",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/SBST2018-77UFPTELICBMLdRdBsqxwb/1NpNSfM8v3RtAphOKcQriJ/vlj87sHHnfl05z1FWKCYM.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Junhwi Kim (KAIST), Minhyuk Kwon (Suresoft Technology), Shin Yoo (KAIST)",
              "abstract": "Test data generation is a tedious and laborious process. Search-based Software Testing (SBST) automatically generates test data optimising structural test criteria using metaheuristic algorithms. In essence, metaheuristic algorithms are systematic trial-and-error based on the feedback of fitness function. This is similar to an agent of reinforcement learning which iteratively decides an action based on the current state to maximise the cumulative reward. Inspired by this analogy, this paper investigates the feasibility of employing reinforcement learning in SBST to replace human designed metaheuristic algorithms. We reformulate the software under test (SUT) as an environment of reinforcement learning. At the same time, we present GunPowder, a novel framework for SBST which extends SUT to the environment. We train a Double Deep Q-Networks (DDQN) agent with deep neural network and evaluate the effectiveness of our approach by conducting a small empirical study. Finally, we find that agents can learn metaheuristic algorithms for SBST, achieving 100% branch coverage for training functions. Our study sheds light on the future integration of deep neural network and SBST.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 11th International Workshop on Search-Based Software Testing SBST 2018 Generating Test Input with Deep Reinforcement Learning 1521445555014 Junhwi Kim KAIST junhwi.kim23@kaist.ac.kr Minhyuk Kwon Suresoft Technology minhyuk@suresofttech.com Shin Yoo KAIST shin.yoo@kaist.ac.kr reinforcement learning test data generation sbst Test data generation is a tedious and laborious process. Search-based Software Testing (SBST) automatically generates test data optimising structural test criteria using metaheuristic algorithms. In essence, metaheuristic algorithms are systematic trial-and-error based on the feedback of fitness function. This is similar to an agent of reinforcement learning which iteratively decides an action based on the current state to maximise the cumulative reward. Inspired by this analogy, this paper investigates the feasibility of employing reinforcement learning in SBST to replace human designed metaheuristic algorithms. We reformulate the software under test (SUT) as an environment of reinforcement learning. At the same time, we present GunPowder, a novel framework for SBST which extends SUT to the environment. We train a Double Deep Q-Networks (DDQN) agent with deep neural network and evaluate the effectiveness of our approach by conducting a small empirical study. Finally, we find that agents can learn metaheuristic algorithms for SBST, achieving 100% branch coverage for training functions. Our study sheds light on the future integration of deep neural network and SBST.",
              "pageNumber": 51,
              "isPageNumberRoman": false
            }
