              "authorNames": "Yves Ledru (Université Grenoble Alpes), Yoann Blein (Université Grenoble Alpes), Lydie du Bousquet (Université Grenoble Alpes), Roland Groz (Université Grenoble Alpes), Arnaud Clere (MinMaxMedical), Fabrice Bertrand (BlueOrtho)",
              "abstract": "The verification of software intensive medical devices can largely benefit from the analysis of their execution traces. Trace points can easily be added to the software, and traces can be used at several stages of the development and maintenance process. In this paper we focus on the TKA system and identify 15 representative properties that should be fulfilled by its traces. We also identify several stages in the product lifecycle where these properties should be evaluated. These properties put requirements on what should be expressible in a trace property language for medical devices.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE International Workshop on Software Engineering in Healthcare Systems SEHS 2018 Requirements for a Trace Property Language for Medical Devices 1521130466642 Yves Ledru Université Grenoble Alpes Yves.Ledru@imag.fr Yoann Blein Université Grenoble Alpes yoann.blein@imag.fr Lydie du Bousquet Université Grenoble Alpes lydie.du-bousquet@imag.fr Roland Groz Université Grenoble Alpes roland.groz@imag.fr Arnaud Clere MinMaxMedical arnaud.clere@minmaxmedical.com Fabrice Bertrand BlueOrtho fabrice.bertrand@blue-ortho.com Monitoring Parametric Events Temporal Specification Trace Analysis Medical Devices The verification of software intensive medical devices can largely benefit from the analysis of their execution traces. Trace points can easily be added to the software, and traces can be used at several stages of the development and maintenance process. In this paper we focus on the TKA system and identify 15 representative properties that should be fulfilled by its traces. We also identify several stages in the product lifecycle where these properties should be evaluated. These properties put requirements on what should be expressible in a trace property language for medical devices.",
