              "id": "7dFlAKG3gxvswsEJyYi2ng",
              "type": "authorPaper",
              "text": "Handling System Complexity in sCPS: Usable Design Space Exploration",
              "articleLocation": "pdfs/SEsCPS2018-5Ys6vFczJb8vtJTIC0U1kP/6Op3uimnyDFRpK66jluwNw/4lDfHbZvEbYBZQd3qYG66K.pdf",
              "extraLocations": [],
              "authorNames": "Sebastian Voss (fortiss GmbH), Eder Johannes (fortiss GmbH)",
              "abstract": "With a growing demand for complex features in smart cyber physical systems, the design of such system is getting increasingly complex. These features demand sound and scalable approaches to deal with the increasing design space. Consequently, standards (e.g. like ISO26262) propose methods and techniques for the systematic development of (in this case: automotive) systems. The growing amount of functionality correspondingly require more powerful electronic platforms and thus methods to deal with the integration. In this paper, we describe drivers for complexity and illustrate how formal methods, namely design space exploration techniques, can be applied to deal with this complexity. This approach is based on requirements defined by the given standards and supports the system designer by a (semi-) automatic approach to handle the complexity in system design – already in early design phases.",
              "searchText": "2018 ACM/IEEE 4th International Workshop on Software Engineering for Smart Cyber-Physical Systems SEsCPS 2018 Handling System Complexity in sCPS: Usable Design Space Exploration 1522046461687 Sebastian Voss fortiss GmbH voss@fortiss.org Eder Johannes fortiss GmbH eder@fortiss.org Model-based Systems Engineering Design Space Exploration Systems Engineering Handling Complexity With a growing demand for complex features in smart cyber physical systems, the design of such system is getting increasingly complex. These features demand sound and scalable approaches to deal with the increasing design space. Consequently, standards (e.g. like ISO26262) propose methods and techniques for the systematic development of (in this case: automotive) systems. The growing amount of functionality correspondingly require more powerful electronic platforms and thus methods to deal with the integration. In this paper, we describe drivers for complexity and illustrate how formal methods, namely design space exploration techniques, can be applied to deal with this complexity. This approach is based on requirements defined by the given standards and supports the system designer by a (semi-) automatic approach to handle the complexity in system design – already in early design phases.",
